Technically, there is no such device as a "transorbital flying vessel." It is likely that two very different historical concepts are being conflated here:
1. The Transorbital Procedure (Medical)
The term "transorbital" is most famously associated with the transorbital lobotomy. This medical procedure was developed by the Italian doctor Amarro Fiamberti in 1937 and later popularized in the United States by Dr. Walter Freeman in 1946. Freeman famously performed these using an "ice pick" style tool inserted through the eye socket (the orbit).  
2. Transatmospheric/Orbital Vessels (Aviation)
If you are looking for early patents on vessels designed to travel into or across orbit:
The Space Shuttle: While many contributed, Maxime Faget is often credited as the "father" of the Space Shuttle design. He held U.S. Patent 3,702,688 (granted in 1972) for a "Space Shuttle Vehicle."  
Transatmospheric Systems: In the late 1980s, Boeing filed several patents for "Horizontal-takeoff transatmospheric launch systems" (such as EP0304590A2), which described vehicles capable of flying from a runway into orbit.  
Early "Flying Saucers": There are several quirky patents for circular craft, such as Lester Rogers' 1966 patent for a "Flying Saucer Structure" (U.S. Patent 3,394,906).  
